# ============================================================================
# Environment Configuration for Backup/Restore Script
# ============================================================================
#
# AUTOMATIC LOADING:
# The script automatically sources this file if named .env and placed in the
# 1. Copy and secure this file:
#    cp .env.example .env
#    chmod 600 .env
# 2. Update `.env` file if needed:
#    nano .env  (or use your preferred editor)
# 3. Source the env file.
#    source .env
# 4. Start using the script:
#    ./backup-restore.sh <import|export>...
#
# 4. Run the script normally - .env is automatically loaded:
#    ./backup-restore.sh export opensearch rag-dev opensearch.tar.gz
#
# ============================================================================

# OpenSearch Admin Password
# 
# IMPORTANT: 
# - If you changed the OpenSearch password during deployment, set it here
# - Default password works for standard deployments but NOT recommended for production
#
# Uncomment and set your password:
# OPENSEARCH_PASSWORD=YourCustomPasswordHere

# ============================================================================
# USAGE EXAMPLES:
# ============================================================================
#
# Option 1: Use default password (for testing/development)
#   Just run the script without creating .env file:
#   ./backup-restore.sh export opensearch rag-dev opensearch.tar.gz
#   (Script will show warning about using default password)
#
# Option 2: Set custom password in .env (recommended for production)
#   1. Create .env: cp .env.example .env
#   2. Edit .env and uncomment OPENSEARCH_PASSWORD line
#   3. Set your password: OPENSEARCH_PASSWORD=MySecurePassword123
#   4. Run script - .env is automatically loaded:
#      ./backup-restore.sh export opensearch rag-dev opensearch.tar.gz
#
# Full backup workflow:
#   ./backup-restore.sh export opensearch rag-dev opensearch.tar.gz
#   ./backup-restore.sh export digitize rag-dev digitize.tar.gz
#
# Full restore workflow:
#   ./backup-restore.sh import opensearch rag-dev opensearch.tar.gz
#   ./backup-restore.sh import digitize rag-dev digitize.tar.gz
#
# ============================================================================
# HOW IT WORKS:
# ============================================================================
#
# The script automatically checks for .env file in the script directory:
# 1. If .env exists → automatically sources it and loads variables
# 2. If .env doesn't exist → uses default password with warning
# 3. Environment variables set before running script take precedence
#
# Password priority order:
# 1. Environment variable (if set before running script)
# 2. .env file (if exists in script directory)
#
# You do NOT need to manually source the .env file!
# The script does it automatically when you run it.
#
# ============================================================================
# SECURITY NOTES:
# ============================================================================
#
# ⚠️  IMPORTANT:
# 1. Never commit .env files with real passwords to version control
# 2. Ensure .env is in .gitignore
# 3. Use strong passwords in production (min 12 characters, mixed case, numbers, symbols)
# 4. Restrict file permissions: chmod 600 .env
# 5. Keep .env file in the same directory as the backup script
# 6. Rotate passwords regularly
# ============================================================================

